definition.value: A carotenol that is beta,beta-carotene carrying two hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 3' (the 3R,3'S-diastereomer). It is rarely found in diet and is believed to be formed at the macula by metabolic transformations of ingested carotenoids.

label.value: EC 6.3.5.* (carbon-nitrogen ligases with glutamine as amido-N-donor) inhibitor

definition.value: An EC 6.3.* (C-N bond-forming ligase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of any carbon-nitrogen ligases with glutamine as amido-N-donor (EC 6.3.5.*).
An EC 6.3.5.* (carbon-nitrogen ligases with glutamine as amido-N-donor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of carbamoyl-phosphate synthase (glutamine-hydrolysing) (EC 6.3.5.5).
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both specified as hexanoyl.
1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as heptanoyl and hexanoyl respectively.
Any EC 6.3.* (C-N bond-forming ligase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of 'other carbon--nitrogen ligases.
Any EC 6.3.4.* (other carbon--nitrogen ligases) inhibitor that interferes with the action of CTP synthase (glutamine hydrolyzing) (EC 6.3.4.2).
1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both specified as heptadecanoyl.
Any EC 6.3.5.* (carbon-nitrogen ligases with glutamine as amido-N-donor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of phosphoribosylformylglycinamidine synthase (EC 6.3.5.3).
An EC 6.3.5.* (carbon-nitrogen ligases with glutamine as amido-N-donor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of GMP synthase (glutamine-hydrolysing) (EC 6.3.5.2).
An N-hexadecanoylphosphatidylethanolamine in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both specified as heptadecanoyl.
An N-oleoylphosphatidylethanolamine in which the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are both specified as heptadecanoyl.
An antagonist that acts on glutamine receptors.
An L-tryptophan derivative in which the indolyl ring nitrogen carries a nitroso substituent.
An L-arginine derivative in which one of the omega-nitrogen atoms carries a nitroso substituent.
A dipeptide that is glutathione in which the amino group on the glutamyl residue has been replaced by an oxo group.
An L-cysteine derivative in which the sulfur atom carries a nitroso substituent.  A cell-permeable low-molecular-weight nitrosothiol and nitric oxide donor.
An N(6)-acyl-L-lysine residue derived from N(6)-hexadecanoyl-L-lysine.
A xylulose phosphate that is D-xylulose carrying two phospho groups at positions 1 and 5.
An EC 4.1.1.* (carboxy-lyase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of ribulose-bisphosphate carboxylase (EC 4.1.1.39).

A branched hexasaccharide derivative consisting of a linear tetrasaccharide unit of beta-L-rhamnose, beta-D-glucose, and two alpha-L-rhamnose residues, linked sequentially (1->4), (1->3) and (1->3), to the non-reducing-end alpha-L-rhamnose residue is also linked (1->2) an alpha-D-glucuronosyl-(1->6)-alpha-D-glucosyl disaccharide branch, the whole linked glycosidically to a 5-aminopentyl group.
A 2-acyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl and the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as hexadecyl and 8-carboxyoctanoyl respectively.
A hydroxy fatty-acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 2-hydroxyoctanoic acid.
An abietane diterpenoid that is ferruginol in which the hydrogen ortho to the phenolic hydroxy group has been replaced by a hydroxy group.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of carnosic acid. The major species at pH 7.3.
A meroterpenoid that is ferruginol which has been substituted by an alpha-hydroxy group at position 6.
A pentacyclic triterpenoid that is olean-12-ene in which the hydrogens at the 3beta and 16beta positions have been replaced by hydroxy groups.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of cochalic acid. The major species at pH 7.3.
A disaccharide derivative consisting of two alpha-L-rhamnosyl residues linked (1->3) and at the reducing end linked glycosidically to a 5-aminopentyl group.
An organic anion that is the conjugate base of (4S)-2,3-dehydroleucocyanidin, obtained by deprotonation of the 3-hydroxy group. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
A disaccharide derivative consisting of a beta-D-glucosyl residue glycosidically linked to a 5-aminopentyl group and which carries at O-3 a beta-L-rhamnosyl residue.
